text: I'm really starting to worry, how much of history are we planning to dramatize and present as fact?  It was a serious historical event that deserves to be remembered, but shouldn't it be done in a more serious and somber way?  Presenting the facts, and recognizing where we stand today in comparison?  I remember old interviews that said that after the planes ran out of bullets they just started strafing real low, and people threw stuff at them, so close you could see their huge smiles.  Those witnesses were so mad, and I don't think we should forget, but we don't want to retain the hate.
author: FurryEskimo

text: The line "Washington is wrong" has me wondering how accurate this will be. I'm sure the fight scenes should be accurate but not how we knew where the attack would be. We had broken their code but there were still designations in the code (locations) we didn't know what the code meant as in this case. We knew they were going to attack someplace but we didn't know what the code's location was. On a hunch we sent a coded message to Midway to broadcast in the clear that they were having a problem with their water purifier (something like that) and a couple days later the Japanese sent a coded message (which we intercepted and decoded) stating that the 'target' was having water issues. THAT's how we knew the attack was heading for Midway.

text: WWII was the pinnacle of aerial combat.  No complex guided weapons systems, simply stick and rudder aviation.  Dog fighting in a prop plane armed with just a .50 cal or 20 mm was an art.  Sadly this depiction of some of the most intense combat sequences in the history of American military aviation will be squandered via unrealistic CGI.  Dunkirk did an excellent job in a few brief scenes.  As a pilot, those dogfighting scenes in the IMAX theatre had my adrenaline pumping as I felt like I was strapped into the cockpit of a RAF Spitfire.  WE NEED A CHRISTOPHER NOLAN BATTLE OF BRITAIN FILM.

text: The actual Battle of Midway is a fascinating subject that needs no embellishment.  The unnecessary love story between a Naval Aviator and Japanese-American Citizen coupled with the splicing of random aerial combat footage really crippled the 1976 Midway movie.  It was very clear that the editors could not tell one aircraft type from another.  Actual history and actual events are very often far more compelling than fictional diversions added to make a movie align with politically correct sentiments.  A high production value movie or series that actually told the story without fictional elements would be incredible. From the trailer, I don't think this is it.

text: Dive Bombers did not attack cross-wise to their target. They attacked lengthwise, that way they do not miss to the left or right. text: The original Midway film was barely serviceable. IMO it ranks right up there with the big budget D-Day flick that preceded it by a¬†about a decade.  I saw Pearl Harbor and yes, it was painful to watch and I will go see this one as well. The Battle of Midway has always been my favorite confrontation of WWII. Had America lost that battle all of the West coast would have been open to attack.   There was so much on the line it is hard to overestimate¬†its importance in history. So, I will go into the theater with a open mind on this version of Midway. Occasionally...very rarely in fact, Hollywood gets it right. Maybe this will be one of those occasions.   If nothing else, perhaps a younger generation will be inclined to do their own research and reading about WWII and specifically Midway. Unfortunately, we are losing our veterans at a alarming rate and soon WWII will be reduced to words in books and a few reels of film. We desperately NEED to rekindle interest in that time¬†in history. or, we may be forced to relive it all again.
